SIMPLE: elector
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elector
<hw>E*lect"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr.
<ets>eligere</ets>: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧lecteur</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who elects, or has the right of choice; a person
who is entitled to take part in an election, or to give his vote in
favor of a candidate for office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, specifically, in any country, a person
legally qualified to vote.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In the old German empire, one of the princes
entitled to choose the emperor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of the persons chosen, by vote of the people in
the United States, to elect the President and Vice President.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elector</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Elector
<hw>E*lect"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧lectoral</ets>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to an election or to
electors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In favor of the <qex>electoral</qex> and other princes.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Electoral college</b></col>, <cd>the body of princes
formerly entitled to elect the Emperor of Germany; also, a name
sometimes given, in the United States, to the body of electors chosen by
the people to elect the President and Vice President.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electorality</ent>⟦br⟧
